<p>NPL 2/2014 
</p>
<p><b>Nepal  
</b></p>
<p> 
</p>
<p> 
</p>
<p><b>Disappearances;  
</b></p>
<p><b>Summary 
</b></p>
<p><b>executions;  
</b></p>
<p><b>Torture;  Truth, 
</b></p>
<p><b>justice, reparation 
</b></p>
<p><b>&amp; guarantees on 
</b></p>
<p><b>non-rec;  Violence 
</b></p>
<p><b>against women;   
</b></p>
<p>Alleged incompatibility of the recently adopted Nepal Act on the Commission on 
</p>
<p>Investigation of Disappeared Persons, Truth and Reconciliation, 2071 (2014), with 
</p>
<p>international obligations. According to the information received, the Act, adopted on 
</p>
<p>25 April 2014, is incompatible with international obligations in the areas of 1) the 
</p>
<p>competence of the Commission to recommend amnesties for perpetrators, including 
</p>
<p>for gross violations of human rights and serious violations of international 
</p>
<p>humanitarian law, 2) the competence of the Commission to initiate reconciliation 
</p>
<p>processes in the absence of a request by the victim or the offender, and 3) the selection 
</p>
<p>procedures for Commission members. 
</p>
<p>12/12/2014 
</p>
<p> 
</p>
<p> 
</p>
