<p><b>Slavery;  
</b></p>
<p><b>Trafficking;   
</b></p>
<p> 
</p>
<p>Alleged trafficking of migrant workers for the purpose of labour exploitation and debt 
</p>
<p>bondage by Vita Food Factory, a Thai business enterprise. According to the 
</p>
<p>information received, Vita Food Factory has confiscated migrant workers 
</p>
<p>identification documents and work permits, and placed them into debt bondage with 
</p>
<p>the involvement of labour brokers. It is also reported that migrant workers employed 
</p>
<p>by Vita Food Company have been made to pay very high documentation and brokers 
</p>
<p>fees respectively to the company and labour brokers who deceived them by using false 
</p>
<p>job advertisements. The company allegedly continues to be in violation of Thai labour 
</p>
<p>laws with regards to minimum wages, working hours, entitlement to paid sick leave 
</p>
<p>and conditions of work. This same issue was the subject of a previous communication 
</p>
<p>sent to the Government of Thailand on 7 April 2014, see a/HRC/27/72, case no. THA 
</p>
<p>2/2014. 
</p>
