<p>USA 12/2013 
</p>
<p><b>United States of 
</b></p>
<p><b>America  
</b></p>
<p> 
</p>
<p> 
</p>
<p><b>Independence of 
</b></p>
<p><b>judges and 
</b></p>
<p><b>lawyers;  
</b></p>
<p><b>Terrorism;  
</b></p>
<p><b>Torture;   
</b></p>
<p> 
</p>
<p>Alleged torture during interrogation to coerce a confession used to incriminate and 
</p>
<p>substantiate a conviction for participating in terrorist activities in Saudi Arabia; alleged 
</p>
<p>prolonged solitary confinement. According to the information received, on 11 June 
</p>
<p>2003, Mr Ahmed Abu Ali was arrested in Medina, Saudi Arabia upon the request of the 
</p>
<p>United States, beaten and whipped in prison until he confessed to being a member of an 
</p>
<p>Al-Qaeda cell. He was transferred to Riyadh where he was allegedly subjected to 
</p>
<p>solitary confinement, and sleep deprivation. Subsequently, he was reportedly transferred 
</p>
<p>to the United States where the confessions he made during the interrogations in Saudi 
</p>
<p>Arabia were used against him as the basis for a conviction for material support to the Al 
</p>
<p>Qaeda network. Mr Ali&#8217;s health condition is deteriorating while he is serving a sentence 
</p>
<p>to life imprisonment without parole in solitary confinement at the United States 
</p>
<p>Penitentiary, Administrative Maximum Facility (ADX).  
</p>
<p>04/08/2014 
</p>
<p>08/08/2014 
</p>
<p> 
</p>
<p> 
</p>
<p> 
</p>
